subsection.p:
gave the function
f(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{x^2y}{x^2+y^2}, & (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, & (x,y)=(0,0). \end{cases}
At the origin, f_x(0,0)=0, \qquad f_y(0,0)=0. So if f were differentiable at the origin, the theorem would force Df(0,0)(\Delta x,\Delta y)=0. The linear approximation would predict f(\Delta x,\Delta y)\approx 0.

image.asymptote:
// 3-D interactive (WebGL) figure.
import graph3;
size(9cm);
currentprojection=orthographic(5,3.4,3);
real f(pair p){return 2-0.16*p.x^2-0.12*p.y^2;}
real fx(real x){return -0.32*x;}
real fy(real y){return -0.24*y;}
surface s=surface(f,(-3,-3),(3,3),24,24);
draw(s, orange+opacity(0.45), meshpen=orange+linewidth(0.15pt));
real a=1.1,b=1.0; real za=f((a,b));
triple P=(a,b,za);
triple du=(1,0,fx(a)), dv=(0,1,fy(b));
real d=1.7;
path3 plane=(P-d*du-d*dv)--(P+d*du-d*dv)--(P+d*du+d*dv)--(P-d*du+d*dv)--cycle;
draw(surface(plane), blue+opacity(0.35));
draw(plane, blue+linewidth(0.5pt));
dot(P, black+5pt); label("$(a,b,f(a,b))$", P, 2N+E);
draw(O--(3.6,0,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O--(0,3.6,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O--(0,0,2.8),gray,Arrow3);
label("$x$",(3.6,0,0),S); label("$y$",(0,3.6,0),E); label("$z$",(0,0,2.8),N);
